@Mimi 

Yes, you are correct. Good point. 

A bit of trivia: V is the stepmother of actor Dylan McDermott.

@Y 

I thought that clue was questionable - joint = spliff, but reefer = cannabis.

I.e., would "Cigarette" be a good clue for TOBACCO? (I think not.)

@bubbacat 

It’s a themeless puzzle. 




>>>

@CS 

I had to put this down and come back to it a few times. Brisk walk always helps. NW was quite tough, but SE was last to fall for me.



cc: emu

@Bonnie 

Thank you for your good wishes, Bonnie.  I don't know what strain it is because the test only detects the presence of the Covid virus.  Genomic sequencing would have to be done to identify the variant and that would be cost prohibitive for the general population.  I think it's done mainly for wastewater to determine what strains are most prevalent, but I'm not a scientist, and I don't even play one on TV, so take what I say with a grain of salt.

I'm so surprised that no one in your circle has had Covid yet.  Almost everyone we know has had it, and sadly, a couple died from it early in the pandemic.  Since you're having cold symptoms and there is such an overlap with Covid symptoms, you might want to do a test to make sure it's not Covid so you can take precautions to avoid spreading it to others.

@Mean Old Lady Gilbert & Sullivan, perhaps?

"Till then, enjoy your dolce far niente."
--"With pleasure, nobody contradicente."

@Andrew It was a tough corner for me too and I came here to the comments looking for answers.

Could you save the CAPS for the correct answers, please? CORER, not CidER for example? DETER, not DEfER.

I mean, is it Tee off or Tee pee? You're not helping anyone with the puzzle, just adding to confusion.

@Jennifer 

I followed the same route to DETER as you did, with each successive answer seemingly getting farther and farther away from the clue.

My takeaway from that (and AGILE) is to remember them for next time!

@Carol 

I had APE and RED TAPE early on, as well as HEE. Thought of CUTE, too, but thought that was too cute.

Le sigh.

@Geoffrey King 

PREACH! I was not at all AGILE in the NW corner; not an EASYREAD at all. :( 

I really felt I was out of my LEAGUE there.

@kilaueabart

Think of the phrase “seeing red.” When one is in a red hot rage, one is in a furor. 

That’s how I understood it.

@Rich in Atlanta - Weird! I remember my Dad telling that one when I was a kid. He was fond of shaggy-dog stories, the longer the better. 

Anyway, for some reason I had thought of this joke, and almost shared it with someone, earlier this week. 

(This may be an interesting example to the Baader-Meinhof phenomenon that came up in the comments yesterday or the day before.)

@Peter Rozman 

SINGES not SIMILAR NGES
🤦‍♂️

@Henry Su 

Price Caldwell's interpretation is very good and insightful. I subscribe to it and to applying it to this puzzle. Between you, Al from Pittsburgh and Puzzlemucker I think you're onto it. Thing as idea; idea as thing. I can ponder that one endlessly.




Emu as idea; idea as emu.

@JenB 

Are you sure it was autocorrect?

Maybe ... whether you knew it or not, your mind was transfixed by the blackbird whirling in the autumn winds. 😉

@Eric Merriam Webster's second definition of "agile" is "having a quick resourceful and adaptable character." 

Merriam Webster's third definition of "flexible" is "characterized by a ready capability to adapt to new, different, or changing requirements."

Since both words can mean "able to adapt", I suppose we will need to be flexible/agile to adapt to this revelation.
